WEBVTT

00:00:03.632 --> 00:00:08.277
In October 2018, Lion Air Flight 610 departed

00:00:08.337 --> 00:00:11.721
Jakarta and crashed into the Java Sea thirteen

00:00:11.721 --> 00:00:16.046
minutes after takeoff. All 189 people on board

00:00:16.126 --> 00:00:18.568
were killed. Five months later,

00:00:18.608 --> 00:00:25.216
in March 2019, Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302 departed

00:00:25.336 --> 00:00:30.061
Addis Ababa and crashed six minutes after takeoff.

00:00:30.061 --> 00:00:33.189
All 157 people on board were killed.

00:00:34.072 --> 00:00:38.443
Both aircraft were Boeing 737 MAX 8s.

00:00:38.443 --> 00:00:40.870
Both crews had fought the same automated system.

00:00:41.772 --> 00:00:44.580
Both had lost. In the months that followed,

00:00:45.282 --> 00:00:48.569
investigators, regulators, and a congressional

00:00:48.629 --> 00:00:51.555
committee examined how two brand-new aircraft from the

00:00:51.615 --> 00:00:54.321
world's most experienced commercial aviation

00:00:54.381 --> 00:00:57.126
manufacturer had been delivered to airlines with a

00:00:57.186 --> 00:01:00.132
flight control system that could overpower the pilots,

00:01:00.854 --> 00:01:02.858
that depended on a single sensor for its

00:01:02.938 --> 00:01:05.886
inputs, and that had not been fully described

00:01:06.347 --> 00:01:08.211
in the flight manuals the pilots were trained

00:01:08.331 --> 00:01:11.537
on. This episode is not about one faulty

00:01:11.618 --> 00:01:14.042
sensor. It is about what happens when a

00:01:14.082 --> 00:01:16.046
company tries to preserve the appearance of the

00:01:16.106 --> 00:01:19.112
old system while redesigning around a new physical

00:01:19.192 --> 00:01:22.707
reality and resolves the contradiction in software the

00:01:22.767 --> 00:01:24.148
pilot cannot clearly see.

00:01:24.208 --> 00:01:28.412
The Boeing 737 first flew in 1967.

00:01:28.833 --> 00:01:31.555
Over the following five decades it became the

00:01:31.595 --> 00:01:35.299
world's bestselling jetliner, accumulated an enormous

00:01:35.379 --> 00:01:37.541
global maintenance and training infrastructure,

00:01:38.401 --> 00:01:41.384
and underwent continuous revision and modernization

00:01:42.065 --> 00:01:44.727
while retaining enough commonality across variants

00:01:44.807 --> 00:01:47.790
that pilots could transition between versions with

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:51.495
limited additional training. That commonality was not

00:01:51.555 --> 00:01:54.440
incidental. It was commercially valuable.

00:01:55.402 --> 00:01:59.310
Airlines operating mixed fleets of 737 variants could

00:01:59.350 --> 00:02:01.554
schedule pilots across aircraft types,

00:02:02.195 --> 00:02:05.121
reduce training costs, and avoid the expense of

00:02:05.121 --> 00:02:06.664
full type rating transitions.

00:02:07.766 --> 00:02:10.651
The 737's longevity was inseparable from its

00:02:10.731 --> 00:02:14.384
reputation for consistency. In December 2010,

00:02:15.306 --> 00:02:18.189
Boeing's primary competitor launched the A320neo

00:02:18.269 --> 00:02:21.033
program, featuring more fuel-efficient engines.

00:02:22.034 --> 00:02:24.517
The announcement was a significant competitive event.

00:02:25.498 --> 00:02:27.141
Airlines responded with interest.

00:02:28.002 --> 00:02:31.106
Boeing faced a choice: develop an entirely new

00:02:31.206 --> 00:02:34.049
aircraft, which would take years and cost billions,

00:02:34.790 --> 00:02:36.713
or modernize the 737 again.

00:02:36.753 --> 00:02:40.117
Boeing chose to modernize.

00:02:40.299 --> 00:02:42.642
The result was the 737 MAX.

00:02:43.684 --> 00:02:46.488
The MAX used a new engine the CFM

00:02:46.548 --> 00:02:49.392
LEAP that was larger and more fuel-efficient than

00:02:49.453 --> 00:02:52.898
its predecessor. The engine's size required it to

00:02:52.958 --> 00:02:54.420
be mounted differently on the wing:

00:02:55.061 --> 00:02:57.565
further forward and higher up than on earlier

00:02:57.585 --> 00:03:01.851
737 variants. That repositioning changed the

00:03:01.931 --> 00:03:04.936
aircraft's aerodynamic behavior at high angles of

00:03:04.976 --> 00:03:10.003
attack. Specifically, under certain conditions,

00:03:10.003 --> 00:03:12.167
the new engine placement caused the nose to

00:03:12.228 --> 00:03:14.051
pitch up more than it had on previous

00:03:14.111 --> 00:03:17.498
variants. This was a handling difference that could,

00:03:17.559 --> 00:03:21.366
in principle, require pilots to learn new procedures

00:03:21.386 --> 00:03:23.411
or require a new type rating.

00:03:24.413 --> 00:03:27.519
Either outcome would erode the commonality argument.

00:03:27.519 --> 00:03:30.544
The training cost advantage one of the central

00:03:30.604 --> 00:03:34.370
commercial justifications for the MAX program depended

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:36.433
on the MAX flying like a 737.

00:03:36.773 --> 00:03:40.379
So Boeing designed a software system to make

00:03:40.439 --> 00:03:41.220
it fly like one.

00:03:42.382 --> 00:03:45.146
The Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System

00:03:46.128 --> 00:03:49.693
MCAS was introduced to compensate for the MAX's

00:03:49.833 --> 00:03:53.439
changed pitch behavior at high angles of attack.

00:03:54.009 --> 00:03:56.233
When the system detected conditions that could lead

00:03:56.294 --> 00:03:59.580
to a nose-high attitude, it automatically pushed the

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:02.686
nose down by trimming the horizontal stabilizer.

00:04:03.708 --> 00:04:06.815
In its original design, MCAS was a relatively

00:04:06.915 --> 00:04:10.191
limited system. It operated in a narrow flight

00:04:10.252 --> 00:04:13.256
envelope, moved the stabilizer a modest amount,

00:04:13.957 --> 00:04:16.401
and was not considered significant enough to require

00:04:16.521 --> 00:04:19.326
prominent disclosure in the flight crew operations

00:04:19.406 --> 00:04:22.871
manual. The FAA's certification process,

00:04:22.931 --> 00:04:25.716
which delegated substantial technical review authority

00:04:26.236 --> 00:04:28.800
to Boeing's own engineers, did not flag it

00:04:28.861 --> 00:04:31.465
as a major new system requiring special pilot

00:04:31.485 --> 00:04:34.049
awareness. Then the design changed.

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:38.235
As flight testing proceeded, the parameters of MCAS

00:04:38.275 --> 00:04:41.379
were expanded. The system was authorized to move

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:44.925
the stabilizer more up to 2.5 degrees per

00:04:45.005 --> 00:04:48.570
activation, compared to the original 0.6 degrees.

00:04:49.652 --> 00:04:52.396
It was authorized to activate repeatedly if the

00:04:52.436 --> 00:04:55.712
triggering conditions persisted. And it continued to

00:04:55.752 --> 00:04:58.658
rely on input from a single angle-of-attack sensor.

00:04:59.861 --> 00:05:02.827
A single sensor. On an aircraft where the

00:05:02.907 --> 00:05:04.992
system that read that sensor could push the

00:05:05.052 --> 00:05:07.377
nose toward the ground with enough authority to

00:05:07.457 --> 00:05:09.261
overpower a crew that did not know what

00:05:09.301 --> 00:05:12.047
was happening, or was not clearly prepared for

00:05:12.087 --> 00:05:14.512
the precise sequence of actions needed to stop

00:05:14.532 --> 00:05:17.977
it. When the 737 MAX entered service,

00:05:18.638 --> 00:05:21.261
pilots were not told MCAS existed by name.

00:05:22.002 --> 00:05:24.004
The system was not described in the standard

00:05:24.084 --> 00:05:25.926
flight crew operations manual.

00:05:26.727 --> 00:05:29.010
The training materials that accompanied the MAX's

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:31.012
entry into service were designed around the

00:05:31.072 --> 00:05:34.396
commonality argument the MAX was presented as a

00:05:34.476 --> 00:05:36.479
familiar aircraft with improved engines,

00:05:37.219 --> 00:05:39.362
not as an aircraft with a new automated

00:05:39.422 --> 00:05:42.145
flight control system that behaved in ways previous

00:05:42.165 --> 00:05:46.371
737s had not. The rationale was coherent within

00:05:46.431 --> 00:05:49.896
its own logic. MCAS was designed to make

00:05:49.916 --> 00:05:51.499
the MAX handle like a 737.

00:05:53.061 --> 00:05:54.163
If it worked as intended,

00:05:54.704 --> 00:05:56.286
pilots would never know it was there.

00:05:56.326 --> 00:05:59.892
Describing a transparent background system in detail

00:05:59.932 --> 00:06:01.875
would raise questions about why it was needed,

00:06:02.576 --> 00:06:04.619
which would raise questions about how different the

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:07.523
MAX actually was, which would undermine the

00:06:07.583 --> 00:06:09.927
commonality argument that justified the limited

00:06:09.987 --> 00:06:13.516
training program. The system was hidden from pilots

00:06:13.636 --> 00:06:17.001
not through malice, but because its visibility would

00:06:17.041 --> 00:06:18.002
have cost too much.

00:06:19.344 --> 00:06:23.329
On October 29, 2018, the crew of Lion

00:06:23.329 --> 00:06:26.633
Air 610 encountered repeated uncommanded nose-down

00:06:26.693 --> 00:06:28.716
inputs beginning shortly after takeoff.

00:06:29.637 --> 00:06:32.661
The aircraft's angle-of-attack sensor the left one,

00:06:33.062 --> 00:06:36.426
which fed MCAS had been providing erroneous readings

00:06:36.486 --> 00:06:38.088
since a previous flight.

00:06:38.507 --> 00:06:39.789
The crew fought the inputs.

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:41.491
The aircraft pitched down.

00:06:42.453 --> 00:06:44.255
It entered the Java Sea at high speed.

00:06:45.377 --> 00:06:47.480
The flight data recorder from Lion Air 610

00:06:48.542 --> 00:06:50.064
showed clearly what had happened.

00:06:50.845 --> 00:06:53.248
Boeing and the FAA were informed.

00:06:54.130 --> 00:06:57.174
An emergency airworthiness directive was issued.

00:06:57.323 --> 00:07:00.146
It described a runaway stabilizer condition and

00:07:00.186 --> 00:07:02.869
directed pilots to follow existing procedures for

00:07:02.929 --> 00:07:05.591
handling it. It did not name MCAS.

00:07:06.492 --> 00:07:12.799
Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302 departed Addis Ababa on

00:07:12.859 --> 00:07:17.423
March 10, 2019, four months after Lion Air

00:07:17.423 --> 00:07:21.427
610. The crew encountered the same system,

00:07:21.848 --> 00:07:24.290
the same failure mode, the same inputs.

00:07:25.071 --> 00:07:27.093
They had been issued the directive.

00:07:27.394 --> 00:07:29.616
They attempted the runaway-stabilizer response

00:07:29.696 --> 00:07:31.098
described after Lion Air.

00:07:31.939 --> 00:07:34.101
It was not sufficient to save the aircraft.

00:07:34.121 --> 00:07:40.267
157 people died. The 737 MAX was grounded

00:07:40.367 --> 00:07:42.089
worldwide two days later.

00:07:42.109 --> 00:07:44.631
To understand how this happened,

00:07:45.092 --> 00:07:47.234
you have to trace five conditions that were

00:07:47.314 --> 00:07:49.736
present long before either aircraft took off.

00:07:50.797 --> 00:07:53.921
The first: a competitive business pressure became a

00:07:54.041 --> 00:07:57.075
design requirement. The decision to match the

00:07:57.176 --> 00:08:01.745
A320neo's timeline by extending the 737 rather than

00:08:01.805 --> 00:08:05.213
developing a new aircraft placed a specific constraint

00:08:05.573 --> 00:08:08.339
on the MAX program: the result had to

00:08:08.379 --> 00:08:10.704
be certifiable as a variant of an existing

00:08:10.784 --> 00:08:13.875
type, with training differences that airlines could

00:08:13.955 --> 00:08:17.480
manage within their existing 737 programs.

00:08:18.662 --> 00:08:21.145
That constraint was not an engineering requirement.

00:08:21.846 --> 00:08:22.928
It was a commercial one.

00:08:23.869 --> 00:08:26.473
But it shaped every subsequent engineering decision,

00:08:27.314 --> 00:08:29.537
because any outcome that threatened the commonality

00:08:29.618 --> 00:08:32.281
argument threatened the program's competitive

00:08:32.361 --> 00:08:37.693
rationale. The second: MCAS grew in authority during

00:08:37.733 --> 00:08:41.017
development. The system that entered service was not

00:08:41.037 --> 00:08:42.598
the system originally designed.

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:47.082
The expansion of MCAS's authority more stabilizer

00:08:47.122 --> 00:08:50.986
movement, repeated activations, the same single-sensor

00:08:50.986 --> 00:08:53.809
input was driven by flight test results that

00:08:53.869 --> 00:08:56.371
required more compensation than the original design

00:08:56.411 --> 00:08:59.994
had provided. Each expansion was reviewed and accepted

00:09:00.054 --> 00:09:03.559
within the program. None triggered a reassessment of

00:09:03.639 --> 00:09:06.604
whether the system had become something qualitatively

00:09:06.684 --> 00:09:09.448
different from what had originally been certified.

00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:12.493
A system that started as a background trim

00:09:12.553 --> 00:09:14.797
function had become, by the time it reached

00:09:14.857 --> 00:09:19.525
service, a powerful automated input capable of forcing

00:09:19.565 --> 00:09:20.987
the aircraft into a dive.

00:09:21.968 --> 00:09:24.613
The process that evaluated it was calibrated to

00:09:24.653 --> 00:09:27.918
the system's origin, not its final state.

00:09:28.354 --> 00:09:32.459
The third: single-sensor dependency was accepted as

00:09:32.519 --> 00:09:36.683
sufficient. MCAS relied on one angle-of-attack sensor.

00:09:37.444 --> 00:09:39.526
A single point of failure in a system

00:09:39.586 --> 00:09:43.050
with the authority to override pilot inputs.

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:46.174
The rationale, as documented in the subsequent

00:09:46.214 --> 00:09:50.138
investigations, was that MCAS was intended as a

00:09:50.218 --> 00:09:53.862
supplement to existing protections that other systems

00:09:53.922 --> 00:09:56.405
and procedures would catch a sensor failure before

00:09:56.565 --> 00:10:00.614
MCAS became dangerous. That assumption required pilots

00:10:00.675 --> 00:10:02.979
to recognize a failure mode that had not

00:10:03.019 --> 00:10:05.585
been described to them, in an aircraft they

00:10:05.625 --> 00:10:07.048
had been told was like the one they

00:10:07.108 --> 00:10:09.953
already knew, under high workload conditions,

00:10:10.555 --> 00:10:12.198
in the seconds after takeoff.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:16.165
The fourth: pilot knowledge and training were limited

00:10:16.185 --> 00:10:18.028
to preserve aircraft commonality.

00:10:18.048 --> 00:10:21.072
The decision not to name or describe MCAS

00:10:21.072 --> 00:10:23.756
in standard training materials was a product of

00:10:23.796 --> 00:10:25.719
the same logic that drove the program from

00:10:25.759 --> 00:10:29.024
the beginning. Disclosing the system meant explaining

00:10:29.044 --> 00:10:33.095
why it existed. Explaining why it existed meant

00:10:33.155 --> 00:10:35.520
acknowledging that the MAX handled differently from

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:39.147
previous 737s under certain conditions.

00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:43.456
Acknowledging that meant undermining the commonality

00:10:43.516 --> 00:10:46.912
claim. The training omission was not the result

00:10:46.972 --> 00:10:48.995
of someone deciding that pilot knowledge was

00:10:49.015 --> 00:10:51.999
unimportant. It was the result of a system

00:10:52.059 --> 00:10:54.783
in which the commercial argument and the safety

00:10:54.864 --> 00:10:58.509
argument were never clearly separated and in which

00:10:58.589 --> 00:11:01.273
the commercial argument had structural priority.

00:11:02.775 --> 00:11:05.259
The fifth: after the first crash,

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.984
the system was defended as procedure before it

00:11:09.044 --> 00:11:11.548
was admitted as architecture.

00:11:11.865 --> 00:11:14.608
The response to Lion Air 610 was framed

00:11:14.688 --> 00:11:16.370
around pilot training and procedure:

00:11:17.211 --> 00:11:19.813
the existing runaway stabilizer procedure covered the

00:11:19.853 --> 00:11:22.856
scenario, pilots needed to know to apply it,

00:11:23.457 --> 00:11:25.679
the airworthiness directive would address the gap.

00:11:26.720 --> 00:11:28.863
That framing was technically defensible.

00:11:29.844 --> 00:11:31.385
The procedure did exist.

00:11:32.186 --> 00:11:33.868
It was theoretically applicable.

00:11:34.849 --> 00:11:36.931
What the framing avoided was the architectural

00:11:37.011 --> 00:11:40.431
question: whether a system with MCAS's authority,

00:11:41.012 --> 00:11:42.336
fed by a single sensor,

00:11:42.397 --> 00:11:47.191
undisclosed to pilots, represented a design that

00:11:47.231 --> 00:11:50.461
should require a different response than a procedural

00:11:50.501 --> 00:11:56.395
reminder. Ethiopian Airlines 302 answered that

00:11:56.475 --> 00:11:59.558
question. The congressional investigation that

00:11:59.638 --> 00:12:01.480
followed produced some of the most direct

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:03.242
documentation of the failure mode.

00:12:04.283 --> 00:12:07.186
Internal Boeing communications showed employees

00:12:07.246 --> 00:12:10.930
expressing concern about MCAS, about pressure to limit

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:13.993
simulator training, about the distance between what

00:12:14.093 --> 00:12:17.917
pilots knew and what the aircraft could do.

00:12:17.917 --> 00:12:22.303
One message, from 2017, described the aircraft as

00:12:22.383 --> 00:12:25.046
designed by clowns supervised by monkeys.

00:12:25.867 --> 00:12:27.469
It was written by a Boeing employee.

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:29.912
It was not shared with the FAA during

00:12:29.993 --> 00:12:33.477
certification. The investigations found systemic

00:12:33.577 --> 00:12:36.841
failures at Boeing and at the FAA's oversight

00:12:36.881 --> 00:12:40.049
structure. The delegation of certification authority

00:12:40.109 --> 00:12:42.838
to Boeing's own engineers, which had been standard

00:12:42.898 --> 00:12:45.707
practice for decades, had not been matched with

00:12:45.767 --> 00:12:48.737
sufficient independent review of systems whose scope

00:12:48.797 --> 00:12:51.144
and authority had changed during development.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:55.344
The 737 MAX returned to service in November

00:12:55.364 --> 00:12:58.990
2020, after extensive redesign of MCAS,

00:12:59.651 --> 00:13:02.335
new pilot training requirements that explicitly named

00:13:02.395 --> 00:13:05.159
and described the system, and revised sensor

00:13:05.239 --> 00:13:07.302
architecture requiring inputs from both

00:13:07.302 --> 00:13:11.428
angle-of-attack sensors before MCAS could activate.

00:13:11.863 --> 00:13:14.291
The aircraft that returned to service was meaningfully

00:13:14.391 --> 00:13:16.397
different from the one that had been certified.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.005
Which meant the one that had been certified

00:13:19.025 --> 00:13:22.075
had been meaningfully different from what pilots had

00:13:22.095 --> 00:13:23.038
been told it was.

00:13:24.199 --> 00:13:27.385
The standard telling of the 737 MAX story

00:13:28.107 --> 00:13:31.514
reaches for individual villains executives who

00:13:31.514 --> 00:13:34.740
prioritized profit, engineers who stayed quiet,

00:13:35.622 --> 00:13:37.045
regulators who looked away.

00:13:38.147 --> 00:13:40.191
Those individuals exist in the record,

00:13:40.873 --> 00:13:42.596
and their choices matter.

00:13:43.099 --> 00:13:46.704
But the mechanism that produced two crashes was

00:13:46.744 --> 00:13:49.708
not a conspiracy. It was a system.

00:13:50.729 --> 00:13:53.313
A commercial constraint became a design requirement.

00:13:54.374 --> 00:13:57.278
A design requirement shaped what could be disclosed.

00:13:58.079 --> 00:14:01.163
What could be disclosed shaped what pilots knew.

00:14:01.223 --> 00:14:04.207
What pilots knew determined what they could do

00:14:04.247 --> 00:14:06.029
when the system activated.

00:14:06.810 --> 00:14:08.733
And the system that activated had grown,

00:14:08.773 --> 00:14:12.618
incrementally, into something that the process

00:14:12.678 --> 00:14:16.321
evaluating it had not been recalibrated to assess.

00:14:17.442 --> 00:14:20.625
Each step was taken inside a normal process

00:14:20.705 --> 00:14:22.707
by people who had reviewed the step before

00:14:22.787 --> 00:14:25.389
it. No single decision looks,

00:14:25.930 --> 00:14:28.832
in isolation, like the choice to put 346

00:14:29.253 --> 00:14:32.376
people at fatal risk.

00:14:32.396 --> 00:14:34.377
The chain only becomes visible when you look

00:14:34.417 --> 00:14:34.938
at all of it.

00:14:35.699 --> 00:14:38.221
That is always how these chains work.

00:14:38.241 --> 00:14:39.602
That is why they are so hard to

00:14:39.662 --> 00:14:44.030
stop. The 737 MAX was certified as a

00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:47.253
familiar aircraft. It was sold as a familiar

00:14:47.334 --> 00:14:50.457
aircraft. It was trained as a familiar aircraft.

00:14:51.499 --> 00:14:53.101
The pilots who flew it in its first

00:14:53.141 --> 00:14:54.542
year of service had been told,

00:14:55.243 --> 00:14:58.948
implicitly and explicitly, that what they already knew

00:14:58.988 --> 00:15:02.412
would be sufficient. It was not sufficient.

00:15:03.413 --> 00:15:04.955
What failed was not the sensor,

00:15:05.456 --> 00:15:07.258
though the sensor failed.

00:15:07.258 --> 00:15:09.562
What failed was the architecture of a system

00:15:09.622 --> 00:15:11.666
in which a competitive argument had been allowed

00:15:11.706 --> 00:15:14.431
to function as a safety argument in which

00:15:14.491 --> 00:15:16.795
the demonstration that training costs could be kept

00:15:16.835 --> 00:15:19.219
low had been allowed to stand in for

00:15:19.259 --> 00:15:21.363
the demonstration that pilots had been given what

00:15:21.403 --> 00:15:24.489
they needed. The system pushed the nose down.

00:15:24.529 --> 00:15:26.151
The pilots fought it.

00:15:26.913 --> 00:15:28.215
They had not been given a full,

00:15:28.315 --> 00:15:30.599
explicit account of the failure mode they were

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:33.275
fighting. They had been told there was little

00:15:33.355 --> 00:15:35.564
new to know. The failure was real.

00:15:36.187 --> 00:15:37.552
The cause chain was longer.

00:15:38.556 --> 00:15:41.348
Next time: another design failure.

00:15:42.352 --> 00:15:44.902
Another system that taught itself to ignore what

00:15:44.963 --> 00:15:46.509
it already knew.
